<subSubSection id="ADCE958C813A2E0BB49C716A522CB700" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph id="BA073CC5BABDB6BFA73C036E3A6BB823" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B573DD4722C5E3C2C8081371772FBE9" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName id="EB3138C838E263C7AEA1DA23C7358D84" authorityName="Curran" authorityYear="1927" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Mesembrius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesembrius nigriceps" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="D1AA6D3D84A80A25C5F5A16BB4918286" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Mesembrius nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males lack an apical pile brush on the profemur and have a metatibia which is curved, but less than in 
<taxonomicName id="2C7D5845DDD1A5010C54CDADDE3252ED" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="D44DE0901A8B6312CA86C452DB5D09E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The face ground colour is black (white to yellow in 
<taxonomicName id="B91D4038F993598782D75FA88A49D3A2" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="A4703EE9AFB13328AB5514B3A74BBA3E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The metafemur is curved, has a patch of conspicuous black pile at the base and, perpendicular to this, a stretch of dense black pile on the ventroposterior side. The male is distinguished from any other species (except from 
<taxonomicName id="014BC7575D0F4D4B14988BC2C29F239B" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="5E0E1BC0D3F070C7A3205C44053AA066" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) by the strongly curved metafemur and metatibia. It differs from 
<taxonomicName id="2ECE3D76141A9188AC2B33F3DD08282D" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="9AAD510C5D8D6396B0C01D01D0F378EA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the colour of the face (white to yellow in 
<taxonomicName id="3EC1AF1E8A053AF3D033C3B729BDCED2" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="5CDB119D158EAF7278C82F20B49F3F93" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; black in 
<taxonomicName id="2452FE285F337CDFF041F845500B70F1" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="E4B03073F50E1C52A029E40EA9374BEC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), in the size and shape of the maculae on tergite II which are small and nearly triangular (large and rounded in 
<taxonomicName id="74864F566FAAA168CAB44DCFEC05E4AE" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="ED541D1B738F9B391FD62E6B97F77AD0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and by the broader black medial marking on tergite II (narrow in 
<emphasis id="D37B15066649081911604F009CCEE4F4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
M 
<taxonomicName id="1AF84CF08AA35EA26B9E91B5ED38BAAF" baseAuthorityName="Bezzi" baseAuthorityYear="1912" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Mesembrius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mesembrius strigilatus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="strigilatus">Mesembrius strigilatus</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
). The female is unknown.
</paragraph>
