<subSubSection id="0F0CBEEA7AB7E967E389ED4B48212E6F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="comments">
<paragraph id="A0E5A81E0CF4FE8855F510E4B8C467BD" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3EE1C5C20BF81534349D9E4DC35995D1" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The species is very similar in morphology to 
<taxonomicName id="3351B72C727E51DC664639C57435418B" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="9F75656FC8F3229D943A98B9DDAA724E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and they are sister species in the NJ phylogenetic analysis (but no support for such relationship in the ML analysis). Compared to 
<taxonomicName id="03710DBE859219DBF1115751C570A788" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="331EEA579153212311703DF02374D3C4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="833FD40F07B7BA53B2968089ACB9D3B9" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="45D9ED29911AFD0F514916AC1AC6FF93" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a black face, a less curved metatibia, the yellow maculae on tergite II are smaller and more triangular and the yellow abdominal pile on abdominal tergite IV is not so strongly appressed on the sides. The male surstylus is morphologically also similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="A6E4A47B96649303921242AA9E59F019" genus="M." lsidName="M. strigilatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="strigilatus">
<emphasis id="1C4A80FAED3F02C57EBE463FDF93ABD4" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. strigilatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the thin apex is much longer in 
<taxonomicName id="7FDA9825A29544E6EA7DB70A26E93455" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="0A51343BE1330690315E404174CBB05A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the dorsal surface of the distal half is more convex in 
<taxonomicName id="12F431D14B9E89997EA40197614689D8" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigriceps" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="nigriceps">
<emphasis id="D2CD224A9973A0CEC73019C7760D9B79" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">M. nigriceps</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
